Mike Lynch should be quizzed 'under penalty of perjury'
HP has said it wants Autonomy founder Mike Lynch to answer questions “under penalty of perjury” in the latest stage of a war of wards over allegations of “serious accounting improprieties” at the British technology company.
Mr Lynch has angrily denied any accounting errors and instead blamed HP for mismanaging the business. Photo: Marina Imperi	By Graham Ruddick
6:51PM GMT 27 Nov 2012
Comments
On Tuesday, Mr Lynch published an open letter to the US company’s board calling for HP to publish the evidence behind its allegations, saying he “utterly rejects all allegations of impropriety”.
HP shocked the financial world last week by taking a $8.8bn (£5.5bn) writedown and claiming that Autonomy, which it bought in 2011 for $11.1bn, had inflated its profits by using irregular accounting methods.
In its first public statement since the allegations emerged last week, HP said: “While Dr Lynch is eager for a debate, we believe the legal process is the correct method in which to bring out the facts and take action on behalf of our shareholders. In that setting, we look forward to hearing Dr Lynch and other former Autonomy employees answer questions under penalty of perjury.”
