Michael Portillo says Eddie Mair did Boris Johnson a favour with BBC interview
Michael Portillo, the former Conservative Party politician, says Eddie Mair did Boris Johnson a favour when he grilled the Mayor of London on The Andrew Marr Show.
Boris Johnson is seen as a contender to be Prime Minister By Tim Walker
7:30AM BST 06 Apr 2013
Comments
Once seen as a serious contender for the top job in British politics himself, Michael Portillo doesn’t think Boris Johnson did himself any harm by agreeing to be interviewed by Eddie Mair, who described him during their bruising encounter as “a nasty piece of work.”
“Boris doesn’t seem to have suffered any damage at all,” Portillo tells Mandrake at the launch of The Speedicut Papers at Buck’s club. “It would be difficult for the next interviewer he faces to be able to take the questions much further, so maybe Eddie Mair has done him a favour.”
Portillo, like the Mayor of London, has faced questions about his own private life and would appear, to some extent, to empathise with him. “I think it’s difficult to draw a proper dividing line between a politician as a public figure, and his private life,” he says. “It is a fact of life that people will be asking difficult questions, and, if Boris wants to go to the top, obviously he’ll have to deal with that.” Portillo, like Johnson, knows the importance of politicians saying the right thing at the right time. Two years before he was a candidate in the 2001 leadership election, he said he had “no ambition” to be leader of the Conservative Party.”
Johnson, in 2002, said there was “not a remote possibility” that he would have a crack at the leadership. Related Articles
