Australia declares convicted murderer innocent after 80 years Australia has declared innocent a convicted murderer even though the crime occurred almost 80 years ago and the wrongly-convicted man has been dead for 35 years. Fred McDermott was initially sentenced to death by hanging after his conviction in 1947 but the penalty was commuted to life imprisonment By Jonathan Pearlman, Sydney
8:51AM GMT 28 Nov 2012
The family of Fred McDermott, a sheep shearer, has been fighting to clear his name ever since he was found guilty of the murder of Harry Lavers, who disappeared from his farm in 1936. His family said he never recovered from the taint of the conviction and died in 1977 – "a ruined man". In a unanimous decision today which prompted emotional scenes among Mr McDermott's family, the Court of Criminal Appeal in New South Wales ruled that he had suffered a "substantial miscarriage of justice". It was the first time an Australian court has posthumously quashed a conviction and followed the discovery of the victim's corpse in a cave in rural New South Wales in 2004. "We always believed he was innocent," Mr McDermott's second cousin, Betty Sheelah, said after the decision was handed down. "It's a wonderful day for Fred. I wished he was here to share it. This was a stain on our family history. Today he is finally innocent."
