Mr McDermott was initially sentenced to death by hanging after his conviction in 1947 but the penalty was commuted to life imprisonment. He was freed more than five years later after a Royal Commission and several court appeals, but the conviction was never quashed. The barrister representing Mr McDermott's family said the murder trial had several "unusual, almost freakish" features which led to a miscarriage of justice. The flawed evidence included claims by a woman, Essie King, who said she saw two men near the scene of the crime on the day that Mr Lavers disappeared. Nine years later, she identified Mr McDermott from poorly-shot photographs, including one where Mr McDermott had his eyes closed. There was also evidence that Mr McDermott's de facto wife claimed he had killed Mr Lavers "for a drop of petrol". But the court heard that he was taunted constantly by his wife and would "parrot what she said as his best way of placating her." The family barrister, Tom Molomby, SC, told the court that "the dead matter to the living". "If a person has died, it would seem not only unfair but cruel to close family and friends ... if the conviction could not be quashed," he said. The Crown did not contest the argument of the family and the judges returned with their ruling after a brief adjournment. "We are satisfied the court has jurisdiction to hear and determine the appeal, notwithstanding the death of Mr McDermott," Chief Justice Tom Bathurst said. Outside the court, Ms Sheelah said: "The justice system has made what was bad good." Australia
